%I A394485 #13 Mar 29 2026 15:53:23
%S A394485 1,2,80,428032
%N A394485 Number of horizontally symmetric reduced Latin squares of order 2n.
%C A394485 The sum of symmetric elements a[i, j] and a[i, n+1-j] in a horizontally symmetric reduced Latin square of order n is constant and equal to n+1 for all pairs of elements (with rows and columns numbered from 1 to n and element values from 1 to n), based on the definition given in A287649 by Eduard I. Vatutin. Horizontal symmetry is of interest in the Latin stable marriage problem because the even-sized maximal examples given in A351413 have this property, as do the lower bounds preference profiles specified in A005154 and A065982.
%H A394485 A. T. Benjamin, C. Converse, and H. A. Krieger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0166-218X(95)80006-P">Note. How do I marry thee? Let me count the ways</a>, Discrete Appl. Math. 59 (1995) 285-292 (Section 3 defines vertical reflection relation).
%H A394485 E. G. Thurber, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0012-365X(01)00194-7">Concerning the maximum number of stable matchings in the stable marriage problem</a>, Discrete Math., 248 (2002), 195-219 (Section 10).
%e A394485 For order 4, the a(2)=2 solutions are:
%e A394485   1234...1234
%e A394485   2143...2413
%e A394485   3412...3142
%e A394485   4321...4321
%e A394485 For order 6, the example shown in A351413 is:
%e A394485   123456
%e A394485   214365
%e A394485   365214
%e A394485   456123
%e A394485   541632
%e A394485   632541
%o A394485 (MiniZinc)
%o A394485 int: n = 8;  %reduced Latin squares of even-size order n with horizonal symmetry
%o A394485 % 1, 2, 80, 428032
%o A394485 set of int: Elements = 1..n;
%o A394485 array[Elements, Elements] of var Elements: L;  % the Latin square
%o A394485 include "alldifferent.mzn";
%o A394485 constraint forall(i in Elements) (  % Latin square constraint
%o A394485   alldifferent([L[i, j] | j in Elements]) /\
%o A394485   alldifferent([L[j, i] | j in Elements]));
%o A394485 constraint forall(i in Elements) (  % reduced form
%o A394485   L[1, i] = i /\
%o A394485   L[i, 1] = i);
%o A394485 constraint forall(r in Elements, i in 1..n div 2) ( % horizontal symmetry
%o A394485   L[r, i] + L[r, n + 1 - i] = n + 1);
%o A394485 solve satisfy;
%Y A394485 Cf. A394486, A287649, A287650, A351413, A005154, A065982, A336412, A000315.
%K A394485 nonn,more,new
%O A394485 1,2
%A A394485 _Dan Eilers_, Mar 22 2026
